# Sports O/X
> Rules and facts about popular sports
@languageCode: en
// Swiq — https://swiq.jiun.dev/set/seed.en.sports.sports/

A soccer (football) team has 11 players on the field. | O | Each soccer team fields 11 players, including the goalkeeper.
In basketball, players score by putting the ball through a hoop. | O | Points are scored by shooting the ball through the opponent's hoop.
The Olympic Games are usually held every four years. | O | The Summer and Winter Olympics are each held every four years.
A marathon is about 42 kilometres long. | O | The official marathon distance is 42.195 kilometres.
In baseball, three strikes make an out. | O | A batter is out after three strikes.
Tennis is played with a racket. | O | Players hit the ball over a net using a racket.
A soccer team has 20 players on the field at once. | X | A soccer team has 11 players on the field, not 20.
In golf, the player with the highest score wins. | X | In golf, the lowest score (fewest strokes) wins.
A basketball is smaller than a golf ball. | X | A basketball is much larger than a golf ball.
The Olympic Games are held every year. | X | The Olympic Games are held every four years.
In swimming races, athletes ride bicycles. | X | Swimmers race by swimming; cycling is a separate sport.
A volleyball team has 15 players on the court. | X | A volleyball team has 6 players on the court.
A basketball team has five players on the court at once. | O | Each basketball team fields five players on the court at any one time.
Rugby is played with a round ball. | X | Rugby is played with an oval ball, which makes its bounce hard to predict.
In tennis, a score of zero is called 'love'. | O | Tennis uses the word 'love' to mean a score of zero, as in '15-love'.
In soccer, a hat-trick means scoring five goals in one game. | X | A hat-trick means one player scores three goals in a single game.
The FIFA World Cup is held every four years. | O | The FIFA World Cup, soccer's biggest tournament, takes place every four years.
The Tour de France is a famous running race. | X | The Tour de France is a multi-week cycling race held mainly in France.
In ice hockey, players use sticks to hit a puck. | O | Ice hockey players use sticks to shoot a flat rubber puck into the opponent's goal.
In basketball, a successful shot from beyond the three-point line is worth two points. | X | A shot made from beyond the three-point line is worth three points; shots inside the line are worth two.
A boxing match takes place in a ring. | O | Boxing matches are held in a square platform with ropes called a ring.
Beach volleyball is an event at the Winter Olympics. | X | Beach volleyball is a Summer Olympic sport; the Winter Olympics feature snow and ice sports.
A standard round of golf has 18 holes. | O | A full round of golf is played over 18 holes on the course.
In bowling, knocking down all ten pins with one roll is called a spare. | X | Knocking down all ten pins with the first roll is a strike; a spare uses two rolls.
The butterfly is one of the four main swimming strokes. | O | Competitive swimming has four main strokes: freestyle, backstroke, breaststroke, and butterfly.
Cricket is played with a puck. | X | Cricket is played with a hard ball and a bat; a puck is used in ice hockey.
In baseball, a home run allows the batter to run all the bases and score. | O | A home run, usually hit over the outfield fence, lets the batter and any runners on base score.
Sumo wrestling is a traditional sport of Brazil. | X | Sumo is the traditional national sport of Japan; Brazil is known for football and capoeira.
Table tennis is also known as ping-pong. | O | Table tennis is commonly called ping-pong, after the sound of the ball on the table and paddles.
In American football, a touchdown is worth one point. | X | A touchdown is worth six points, with the chance to add extra points afterward.
A triathlon combines swimming, cycling, and running. | O | A triathlon is a single race made up of three stages: swimming, cycling, and running.
Badminton is played with a heavy metal ball. | X | Badminton is played with a light feathered (or plastic) shuttlecock, not a ball.
In soccer, the goalkeeper is the only player allowed to handle the ball during open play. | O | Only the goalkeeper may use their hands, and only inside their own penalty area.
In tennis, the ball may bounce twice before a player returns it. | X | A player loses the point if the ball bounces twice on their side; it must be returned after at most one bounce.
Fencing is a sport of sword fighting. | O | Fencing is an Olympic combat sport in which athletes duel with blunted swords such as the foil, épée, and sabre.
The 100-metre sprint is a long-distance running event. | X | The 100-metre race is the shortest outdoor sprint; long-distance events include the 5,000 metres and beyond.
